A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the vein. Clinical manifestations include erythema, marked discomfort, swelling, and induration along the course of the infected vein.
A disorder characterized by fear and avoidance of light.
A disorder characterized by an increase in sensitivity of the skin to light.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate a decrease in number of platelets in a blood specimen.
A disorder characterized by an increase in amounts of fluid within the pleural cavity. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough and marked chest discomfort.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the pleural cavity.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the pleura.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the pleura.
A disorder characterized by inflammation focally or diffusely affecting the lung parenchyma.
A disorder characterized by abnormal presence of air in the pleural cavity resulting in the collapse of the lung.
A disorder characterized by an increase in blood pressure in the portal venous system.
A disorder characterized by the formation of a thrombus (blood clot) in the portal vein.
A disorder characterized by excessive mucous secretion in the back of the nasal cavity or throat, causing sore throat and/or coughing.
A disorder characterized by bleeding occurring after a surgical procedure.
A finding of a previously undocumented problem that occurs after a thoracic procedure.
A disorder characterized by unusually early development of secondary sexual features; the onset of sexual maturation begins usually before age 8 for girls and before age 9 for boys.

valueMeaning.longName: Pregnancy, puerperium and perinatal conditions - Other, specify
valueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pregnancy, puerperium and perinatal conditions - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by delivery of a viable infant before the normal end of gestation. Typically, viability is achievable between the twentieth and thirty-seventh week of gestation.

A disorder characterized by premature ovarian failure. Symptoms may include hot flashes, night sweats, mood swings, and a decrease in sex drive. Laboratory findings include elevated luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH.)
A disorder characterized by an episode of lightheadedness and dizziness which may precede an episode of syncope.
A disorder characterized by inflammation of the rectum.
A disorder characterized by expectorated secretions upon coughing.
A finding of protrusion of the intestinal stoma (surgically created opening on the surface of the body) above the abdominal surface.
A finding of displacement of the urostomy.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the prostate gland.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the prostate gland.

A disorder characterized by compression of the urethra secondary to enlargement of the prostate gland. This results in voiding difficulties (straining to void, slow urine stream, and incomplete emptying of the bladder).
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the prostate gland.
A disorder characterized by laboratory test results that indicate the presence of excessive protein in the urine. It is predominantly albumin, but also globulin.
A disorder characterized by an intense itching sensation.
Psychiatric disorders - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by personality change, impaired functioning, and loss of touch with reality. It may be a manifestation of schizophrenia, bipolar disorder or brain tumor.
A disorder characterized by accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues that causes a disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure.
A disorder characterized by the replacement of the lung tissue by connective tissue, leading to progressive dyspnea, respiratory failure or right heart failure.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the lung and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by an increase in pressure within the pulmonary circulation due to lung or heart disorder.
A disorder characterized by a defect in pulmonary valve function or structure.

A disorder characterized by hemorrhagic areas of the skin and mucous membrane. Newer lesions appear reddish in color. Older lesions are usually a darker purple color and eventually become a brownish-yellow color.

A disorder characterized by dysfunction of the corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts of the spinal cord. Symptoms include an increase in the muscle tone in the lower extremities, hyperreflexia, positive Babinski and a decrease in fine motor coordination.

A finding of acute skin inflammatory reaction caused by drugs, especially chemotherapeutic agents, for weeks or months following radiotherapy. The inflammatory reaction is confined to the previously irradiated skin and the symptoms disappear after the removal of the pharmaceutical agent.
A disorder characterized by inflammation involving a nerve root. Patients experience marked discomfort radiating along a nerve path because of spinal pressure on the connecting nerve root.
A disorder characterized by an eruption of papules and pustules, typically appearing in face, scalp, upper chest and back.

A disorder characterized by the presence of macules (flat) and papules (elevated). Also known as morbillform rash, it is one of the most common cutaneous adverse events, frequently affecting the upper trunk, spreading centripetally and associated with pruritis.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed and elevated skin lesion filled with pus.
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a rectal anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the rectum and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the rectal wall and discharged from the anus.
A disorder characterized by ulceration or inflammation of the mucous membrane of the rectum.
A disorder characterized by a necrotic process occurring in the rectal wall.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the normal flow of the intestinal contents in the rectum.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the rectal region.
A disorder characterized by a rupture in the rectal wall.
A disorder characterized by a narrowing of the lumen of the rectum.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed, erosive lesion on the mucosal surface of the rectum.
A disorder characterized by paralysis of the recurrent laryngeal nerve.

valueMeaning.longName: Renal and urinary disorders - Other, specify
valueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Renal and urinary disorders - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by the formation of crystals/kidney stones in the pelvis of the kidney.
A disorder characterized by paroxysmal and severe flank marked discomfort radiating to the inguinal area. Often, the cause is the passage of crystals/kidney stones.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the kidney.

valueMeaning.longName: Reproductive system and breast disorders - Other, specify
valueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Reproductive system and breast disorders - Other, specify

A disorder characterized by impaired gas exchange by the respiratory system resulting in hypoxia and a decrease in oxygenation of the tissues that may be associated with an increase in arterial levels of carbon dioxide.

valueMeaning.longName: Respiratory, thoracic and mediastinal disorders - Other, specify
valueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Respiratory, thoracic and mediastinal disorders - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by an inability to rest, relax or be still.
A disorder characterized by an inability of the ventricles to fill with blood because the myocardium (heart muscle) stiffens and loses its flexibility.
A disorder characterized by the separation of the inner retina layers from the underlying pigment epithelium.
A disorder characterized by a small laceration of the retina, this occurs when the vitreous separates from the retina. Symptoms include flashes and floaters.
A disorder characterized by pathological retinal blood vessels that adversely affects vision.
A disorder characterized by weight gain, dyspnea, pleural and pericardial effusions, leukocytosis and/or renal failure originally described in patients treated with all-trans retinoic acid.
A disorder involving the retina.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the retroperitoneal area.

A disorder characterized by headaches, mental status changes, visual disturbances, and/or seizures associated with imaging findings of posterior leukoencephalopathy. It has been observed in association with hypertensive encephalopathy, eclampsia, and immunosuppressive and cytotoxic drug treatment. It is an acute or subacute reversible condition. Also known as posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome (PRES).
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the nasal mucosal.
A disorder characterized by impairment of right ventricular function associated with low ejection fraction and a decrease in motility of the right ventricular wall.
A disorder characterized by inflammation of the salivary duct.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between a salivary gland and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the salivary gland.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the skin covering the top and the back of the head.
A disorder characterized by involvement of the sclera of the eye.
A disorder characterized by a malformed, lateral curvature of the spine.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the scrotum.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the scrotal area.
A disorder characterized by a sudden, involuntary skeletal muscular contractions of cerebral or brain stem origin.
A disorder characterized by the presence of pathogenic microorganisms in the blood stream that cause a rapidly progressing systemic reaction that may lead to shock.
A finding of tumor-like collection of serum in the tissues.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an increase in the levels of amylase in a serum specimen.

A disorder characterized by a delayed-type hypersensitivity reaction to foreign proteins derived from an animal serum. It occurs approximately six to twenty-one days following the administration of the foreign antigen. Symptoms include fever, arthralgias, myalgias, skin eruptions, lymphadenopathy, chest marked discomfort and dyspnea.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with alternating periods of bradycardia and atrial tachycardia accompanied by syncope, fatigue and dizziness.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with a heart rate less than 60 beats per minute that originates in the sinus node.
A disorder characterized by involvement of the paranasal sinuses.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the face, between the eyes, or upper teeth originating from the sinuses.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with a heart rate greater than 100 beats per minute that originates in the sinus node.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the mucous membranes of the paranasal sinuses.

valueMeaning.longName: Skin and subcutaneous tissue disorders - Other, specify
valueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Skin and subcutaneous tissue disorders - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by the degeneration and thinning of the epidermis and dermis.
A disorder characterized by darkening of the skin due to excessive melanin deposition.
A disorder characterized by loss of skin pigment (e.g., vitiligo).
A disorder characterized by an area of hardness in the skin.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the skin such as cellulitis.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed, erosive lesion on the skin.
A disorder characterized by cessation of breathing for short periods during sleep.
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of an anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures) in the small bowel.
A disorder characterized by ulceration or inflammation of the mucous membrane of the small intestine.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the normal flow of the intestinal contents of the small intestine.
A disorder characterized by a rupture in the small intestine wall.
A disorder characterized by a narrowing of the lumen of the small intestine.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the small intestine.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed, erosive lesion on the mucosal surface of the small intestine.
A disorder characterized by the involuntary expulsion of air from the nose.
Social circumstances - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving soft tissues.
A disorder characterized by a necrotic process occurring in the soft tissues of the lower extremity.
A disorder characterized by a necrotic process occurring in the soft tissues of the upper extremity.
A disorder characterized by characterized by excessive sleepiness and drowsiness.
A disorder characterized by marked discomfort in the throat
A disorder characterized by increased involuntary muscle tone that affects the regions interfering with voluntary movement. It results in gait, movement, and speech disturbances.
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a spermatic cord anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the spermatic cord.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the normal flow of the contents of the spermatic cord.
A finding of traumatic injury to the spine in which the continuity of a vertebral bone is broken.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the spleen.
A finding of narrowing of the gastrointestinal stoma (surgically created opening on the surface of the body).
A disorder characterized by less than 10% total body skin area separation of dermis. The syndrome is thought to be a hypersensitivity complex affecting the skin and the mucous membranes.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving a stoma (surgically created opening on the surface of the body).
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the stomach.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed, erosive lesion on the jejunal mucosal surface close to the anastomosis site following a gastroenterostomy procedure.
A disorder characterized by a high pitched breathing sound due to laryngeal or upper airway obstruction.
A disorder characterized by a decrease or absence of blood supply to the brain caused by obstruction (thrombosis or embolism) of an artery resulting in neurological damage.
An unexpected death that cannot be attributed to a CTCAE term associated with Grade 5.
A disorder characterized by thoughts of taking one's own life.
A disorder characterized by self-inflicted harm in an attempt to end one's own life.
A disorder characterized by fibrotic degeneration of the superficial soft tissues.
A disorder characterized by a blood clot and inflammation involving a superficial vein of the extremities.
A disorder characterized by obstruction of the blood flow in the superior vena cava. Signs and symptoms include swelling and cyanosis of the face, neck, and upper arms, cough, orthopnea and headache.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with a heart rate greater than 100 beats per minute that originates above the ventricles.

valueMeaning.longName: Surgical and medical procedures - Other, specify
valueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Surgical and medical procedures - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by spontaneous loss of consciousness caused by insufficient blood supply to the brain.
A disorder characterized by local dilatation of small vessels resulting in red discoloration of the skin or mucous membranes.
A disorder characterized by abnormal function or appearance of the testis.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the testis.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the testis.
A disorder characterized by occlusion of a vessel by a thrombus that has migrated from a distal site via the blood stream.

A disorder characterized by the presence of microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenic purpura, fever, renal abnormalities and neurological abnormalities such as seizures, hemiplegia, and visual disturbances. It is an acute or subacute condition.
A disorder characterized by noise in the ears, such as ringing, buzzing, roaring or clicking.
A disorder characterized by a pathological process of the teeth occurring during tooth development.
A disorder characterized by a change in tooth hue or tint.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving a tooth.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the tooth.
A disorder characterized by greater than 30% total body skin area separation of dermis. The syndrome is thought to be a hypersensitivity complex affecting the skin and the mucous membranes.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the trachea and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the trachea.
A disorder characterized by an inflammation or ulceration involving the mucous membrane of the trachea.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the lumen of the trachea.
A disorder characterized by a narrowing of the trachea.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the trachea.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the tracheostomy site.
A disorder characterized by a brief attack (less than 24 hours) of cerebral dysfunction of vascular origin, with no persistent neurological deficit.
A disorder characterized by development of a malignancy most probably as a result of treatment for a previously existing malignancy.
A disorder characterized by the uncontrolled shaking movement of the whole body or individual parts.
A disorder characterized by a defect in tricuspid valve function or structure.
A disorder characterized by dysfunction of the trigeminal nerve (fifth cranial nerve).
A disorder characterized by lack of ability to open the mouth fully due to a decrease in the range of motion of the muscles of mastication.
A disorder characterized by metabolic abnormalities that result from a spontaneous or therapy-related cytolysis of tumor cells.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort from a neoplasm that may be pressing on a nerve, blocking blood vessels, inflamed or fractured from metastasis.
A disorder characterized by necrotizing enterocolitis in neutropenic patients.
A disorder characterized by a discrepancy between the lengths of the lower or upper extremities.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the upper gastrointestinal tract (oral cavity, pharynx, esophagus, and stomach).
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the upper respiratory tract (nose, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, larynx, or trachea).
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a ureteral anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a urethral anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the urethra.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between any part of the urinary system and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by urination at short intervals.
A disorder characterized by inability to control the flow of urine from the bladder.
A disorder characterized by accumulation of urine within the bladder because of the inability to urinate.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the urinary tract, most commonly the bladder and the urethra.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the normal flow of contents of the urinary tract.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the urinary tract.
A disorder characterized by a sudden compelling urge to urinate.
A disorder characterized by a change in the color of the urine.
A finding based on test results that indicate urine production is less relative to previous output.
A finding of leakage of contents from a urostomy.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the urostomy.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the urostomy site.
A finding of narrowing of the opening of a urostomy.
A disorder characterized by an itchy skin eruption characterized by wheals with pale interiors and well-defined red margins.
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a uterine anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the uterus and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the uterus.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the endometrium. It may extend to the myometrium and parametrial tissues.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the uterine outlet.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the uterus.
A disorder characterized by a rupture in the uterine wall.
A disorder characterized by inflammation to the uvea of the eye.
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a vaginal anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A disorder characterized by vaginal secretions. Mucus produced by the cervical glands is discharged from the vagina naturally, especially during the childbearing years.
A disorder characterized by an uncomfortable feeling of itching and burning in the vagina.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the vagina and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the vagina.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the vagina.
A disorder characterized by inflammation involving the vagina. Symptoms may include redness, edema, marked discomfort and an increase in vaginal discharge.
A disorder characterized by blockage of vaginal canal.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the vagina.
A disorder characterized by a rupture in the vaginal wall.
A disorder characterized by a narrowing of the vaginal canal.
A disorder characterized by dysfunction of the vagus nerve (tenth cranial nerve).
A finding of leakage due to breakdown of a vas deferens anastomosis (surgical connection of two separate anatomic structures).
A finding of a previously undocumented problem related to the vascular access site.
Vascular disorders - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by inflammation involving the wall of a vessel.

A disorder characterized by a sudden drop of the blood pressure, bradycardia, and peripheral vasodilation that may lead to loss of consciousness. It results from an increase in the stimulation of the vagus nerve.
A finding of damage to a vein.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia that originates in the ventricles.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia without discernible QRS complexes due to rapid repetitive excitation of myocardial fibers without coordinated contraction of the ventricles.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with a heart rate greater than 100 beats per minute that originates distal to the bundle of His.
A disorder characterized by a sensation as if the external world were revolving around the patient (objective vertigo) or as if he himself were revolving in space (subjective vertigo).
A disorder characterized by dizziness, imbalance, nausea, and vision problems.
A disorder characterized by inappropriate masculinization occurring in a female or prepubertal male.
A disorder characterized by a decrease in blood supply due to narrowing or blockage of a visceral (mesenteric) artery.
A finding based on pulmonary function test results that indicate an abnormal vital capacity (amount of exhaled after a maximum inhalation) when compared to the predicted value.
A disorder characterized by bleeding into the vitreous humor.
A disorder characterized by a change in the sound and/or speed of the voice.
A disorder characterized by the reflexive act of ejecting the contents of the stomach through the mouth.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the vulva.
A disorder characterized by excessive tearing in the eyes; it can be caused by overproduction of tears or impaired drainage of the tear duct.
A finding characterized by an unexpected or abnormal increase in overall body weight; for pediatrics, greater than the baseline growth curve.
A finding characterized by a decrease in overall body weight; for pediatrics, less than the baseline growth curve.
A disorder characterized by a high-pitched, whistling sound during breathing. It results from the narrowing or obstruction of the respiratory airways.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an decrease in number of white blood cells in a blood specimen.
A finding of development of a new problem at the site of an existing wound.
A finding of separation of the approximated margins of a surgical wound.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the wound.
A finding of traumatic injury to the wrist joint in which the continuity of a wrist bone is broken.

referenceDocument.name: CDISC Aligned NCI Standard Equivalent CDE
referenceDocument.doctext: This data element is to be used for CDISC aligned data collection in place of CDE 6063561 from the original NCI Standard CRF Template.

referenceDocument.name: MedDRA AE Code (CTCAE v5.0)
referenceDocument.doctext: MedDRA AE Code (CTCAE v5.0)

validValue.description: A disorder characterized by swelling of the abdomen.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the abdominal region.
A disorder characterized by abnormally high acidity (high hydrogen-ion concentration) of the blood and other body tissues.
A disorder characterized by dysfunction of the acoustic nerve (eighth cranial nerve).

A finding based on laboratory test results in which the partial thromboplastin time is found to be greater than the control value. As a possible indicator of coagulopathy, a prolonged partial thromboplastin time (PTT) may occur in a variety of diseases and disorders, both primary and related to treatment.

A disorder characterized by the adrenal cortex not producing enough of the hormone cortisol and in some cases, the hormone aldosterone. It may be due to a disorder of the adrenal cortex as in Addison's disease or primary adrenal insufficiency.
A disorder characterized by progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery.
A disorder characterized by a state of restlessness associated with unpleasant feelings of irritability and tension.
A disorder characterized by an uncomfortable feeling of inner restlessness and inability to stay still; this is a side effect of some psychotropic drugs.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an increase in the level of alanine aminotransferase (ALT or SGPT) in the blood specimen.

A disorder characterized by an increase in sensitivity to the adverse effects of alcohol, which can include nasal congestion, skin flushes, heart dysrhythmias, nausea, vomiting, indigestion and headaches.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an increase in the level of alkaline phosphatase in a blood specimen.
A disorder characterized by abnormally high alkalinity (low hydrogen-ion concentration) of the blood and other body tissues.
A disorder characterized by an adverse local or general response from exposure to an allergen.

A disorder characterized by an inflammation of the nasal mucous membranes caused by an IgE-mediated response to external allergens. The inflammation may also involve the mucous membranes of the sinuses, eyes, middle ear, and pharynx. Symptoms include sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching.
A disorder characterized by a decrease in density of hair compared to normal for a given individual at a given age and body location.
A disorder characterized by the abnormal absence of menses for at least three consecutive menstrual cycles
A disorder characterized by systematic and extensive loss of memory.
A disorder characterized by a tear in the lining of the anus.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the opening in the anal canal to the perianal skin.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the anal region.
A disorder characterized by a narrowing of the lumen of the anal canal.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed, erosive lesion on the mucosal surface of the anal canal.

A disorder characterized by an acute inflammatory reaction resulting from the release of histamine and histamine-like substances from mast cells, causing a hypersensitivity immune response. Clinically, it presents with breathing difficulty, dizziness, hypotension, cyanosis and loss of consciousness and may lead to death.

A disorder characterized by a reduction in the amount of hemoglobin in 100 ml of blood. Signs and symptoms of anemia may include pallor of the skin and mucous membranes, shortness of breath, palpitations of the heart, soft systolic murmurs, lethargy, and fatigability.
A finding of damage to the ankle joint characterized by a break in the continuity of the ankle bone. Symptoms include marked discomfort, swelling and difficulty moving the affected leg and foot.
A disorder characterized by a loss of appetite.
A disorder characterized by an inability to achieve orgasm.
A disorder characterized by a change in the sense of smell.
A disorder characterized by apprehension of danger and dread accompanied by restlessness, tension, tachycardia, and dyspnea unattached to a clearly identifiable stimulus.
A finding of damage to the aorta.
A disorder characterized by the inability to speak. It may result from injuries to the vocal cords or may be functional (psychogenic).
A disorder characterized by cessation of breathing.
A disorder characterized by acute inflammation to the vermiform appendix caused by a pathogenic agent.

A disorder characterized by acute inflammation to the vermiform appendix caused by a pathogenic agent with gangrenous changes resulting in the rupture of the appendiceal wall. The appendiceal wall rupture causes the release of inflammatory and bacterial contents from the appendiceal lumen into the abdominal cavity.
A disorder characterized by inflammation of the arachnoid membrane and adjacent subarachnoid space.
A finding of damage to an artery.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in a joint.
A disorder characterized by inflammation involving a joint.
A disorder characterized by accumulation of serous or hemorrhagic fluid in the peritoneal cavity.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an increase in the level of aspartate aminotransferase (AST or SGOT) in a blood specimen.
A disorder characterized by inhalation of solids or liquids into the lungs.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia without cardiac electrical activity. Typically, this is accompanied by cessation of the pumping function of the heart.
A disorder characterized by lack of coordination of muscle movements resulting in the impairment or inability to perform voluntary activities.
A disorder characterized by the collapse of part or the entire lung.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia without discernible P waves and an irregular ventricular response due to multiple reentry circuits. The rhythm disturbance originates above the ventricles.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with organized rhythmic atrial contractions with a rate of 200-300 beats per minute. The rhythm disturbance originates in the atria.
A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with complete failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction through the AV node to the ventricles.

A disorder characterized by a dysrhythmia with a delay in the time required for the conduction of an electrical impulse through the atrioventricular (AV) node beyond 0.2 seconds; prolongation of the PR interval greater than 200 milliseconds.
A disorder characterized by laboratory test results that indicate complete absence of spermatozoa in the semen.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the back region.
A disorder characterized by the presence of bacteria in the blood stream.
To expel gas noisily from the mouth.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the bile ducts and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the bladder.
A disorder characterized by subject-reported feeling of uncomfortable fullness of the abdomen.

validValue.meaningText: Blood and lymphatic system disorders - Other, specify
validValue.description: Blood and lymphatic system disorders - Other, specify
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate abnormal levels of antidiuretic hormone in the blood specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate a decrease in levels of bicarbonate in a venous blood specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an abnormally high level of bilirubin in the blood. Excess bilirubin is associated with jaundice.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an decrease in levels of corticotrophin in a blood specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate abnormal levels of gonadotrophin hormone in a blood specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate increased levels of lactate dehydrogenase in the blood specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate abnormal levels of prolactin hormone in a blood specimen.
A disorder characterized by visual perception of unclear or fuzzy images.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal body smell resulting from the growth of bacteria on the body.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the bones.
A disorder characterized by underdevelopment of the breast.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the breast.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the breast region.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the bronchus and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by blockage of a bronchus passage, most often by bronchial secretions and exudates.
A disorder characterized by a sudden contraction of the smooth muscles of the bronchial wall.
A finding of injury of the soft tissues or bone characterized by leakage of blood into surrounding tissues.
A disorder characterized by occlusion of the hepatic veins and typically presents with abdominal pain, ascites and hepatomegaly.
A disorder characterized by inflammation of the skin characterized by the presence of bullae which are filled with fluid.

A finding of impaired integrity to the anatomic site of an adverse thermal reaction. Burns can be caused by exposure to chemicals, direct heat, electricity, flames and radiation. The extent of damage depends on the length and intensity of exposure and time until provision of treatment.

A disorder characterized by leakage of intravascular fluids into the extravascular space. This syndrome is observed in patients who demonstrate a state of generalized leaky capillaries following shock syndromes, low-flow states, ischemia-reperfusion injuries, toxemias, medications, or poisoning. It can lead to generalized edema and multiple organ failure.
A disorder characterized by cessation of the pumping function of the heart.
Cardiac disorders - Other, specify
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate increased levels of cardiac troponin I in a biological specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate increased levels of cardiac troponin T in a biological specimen.
A disorder characterized by partial or complete opacity of the crystalline lens of one or both eyes. This results in a decrease in visual acuity and eventual blindness if untreated.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process that arises secondary to catheter use.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an decrease in levels of CD4 lymphocytes in a blood specimen.
A disorder characterized by loss of cerebrospinal fluid into the surrounding tissues.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the uterine cervix.
A disorder characterized by inflammation of the lip.
A disorder characterized by substernal discomfort due to insufficient myocardial oxygenation e.g., angina pectoris.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of marked discomfort in the chest wall.
A disorder characterized by a sensation of cold that often marks a physiologic response to sweating after a fever.
A disorder characterized by inflammation involving the gallbladder. It may be associated with the presence of gallstones.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate higher than normal levels of cholesterol in a blood specimen.
A disorder characterized by accumulation of milky fluid in the peritoneal cavity.
A disorder characterized by a conspicuous change in cognitive function.
A disorder characterized by inflammation of the colon.
A disorder characterized by an abnormal communication between the large intestine and another organ or anatomic site.
A disorder characterized by bleeding from the colon.
A disorder characterized by blockage of the normal flow of the intestinal contents in the colon.
A disorder characterized by a rupture in the colonic wall.
A disorder characterized by a narrowing of the lumen of the colon.
A disorder characterized by a circumscribed, erosive lesion on the mucosal surface of the colon.
A disorder characterized by a deterioration in the ability to concentrate.
A disorder characterized by pathological irregularities in the cardiac conduction system.
A disorder characterized by a lack of clear and orderly thought and behavior.

validValue.meaningText: Congenital, familial and genetic disorders - Other, specify
validValue.description: Congenital, familial and genetic disorders - Other, specify
A disorder characterized by inflammation, swelling and redness to the conjunctiva of the eye.
A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the conjunctiva. Clinical manifestations include pink or red color in the eyes.
A disorder characterized by irregular and infrequent or difficult evacuation of the bowels.
A disorder characterized by sudden, often repetitive, spasmodic contraction of the thoracic cavity, resulting in violent release of air from the lungs and usually accompanied by a distinctive sound.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate an increase in levels of creatine phosphokinase in a blood specimen.
A finding based on laboratory test results that indicate increased levels of creatinine in a biological specimen.

A disorder characterized by signs and symptoms that resemble Cushing's disease or syndrome: buffalo hump obesity, striations, adiposity, hypertension, diabetes, and osteoporosis, usually due to exogenous corticosteroids.
A disorder characterized by a bluish discoloration of the skin and/or mucous membranes.
Newborn death occurring during the first 28 days after birth.
Death that cannot be attributed to a CTCAE term associated with Grade 5.

referenceDocument.name: AEENRTPT; AEENRF
referenceDocument.doctext: This does not map directly to an SDTMIG variable. May be used to populate a value into an SDTMIG relative timing variable such as AEENRF or AEENRTPT. When populating AEENRF, if the value of AEONGO is "Y", the value of "DURING", "AFTER" or "DURING/AFTER" may be used. When populating AEENRTPT, if the value of AEONGO is "Y", the value of "ONGOING" may be used. When AEONGO refers to the Study Reference Period (defined in DM.RFSTDTC to DM.RFENDTC) the SDTMIG variable AEENRF should be populated. When AEONGO is compared to any other time point, the SDTMIG variables AEENRTPT and AEENTPT should be used. Note: AEENRTPT must refer to a time point anchor described in AEENTPT.
